excerpt: A network of modern greenhouses & waterfront parks containing super trees lined with solar cells.
detail_description: Gardens by the Bay is a stunning showcase of modern horticulture and innovative design, nestled in the heart of Singapore. This expansive green space features towering supertrees adorned with solar panels, creating a futuristic atmosphere that feels like stepping into another world. Visitors can explore cooled indoor gardens and themed areas celebrating Singapore's rich cultural diversity, including Malay, Chinese, and Indian influences. While wandering through this urban oasis is free, certain attractions like the magnificent glass-domed flower conservatory do require an entrance fee.
name: Gardens by the Bay

excerpt: Vibrant island with sandy beaches, hotels & a casino, plus golf courses, a theme park & aquarium.
detail_description: Sentosa Island, located off the southern coast of Singapore, is a popular tourist destination known for its beautiful beaches, theme parks, and adventure activities. The island offers a wide range of attractions including Fort Siloso, Fort Siloso Skywalk, Butterfly Park & Insect Kingdom. Visitors can also enjoy upscale hotels and resorts with various dining options serving local and international cuisine. Sentosa Cove is a residential area on the island featuring luxurious mansions and condominium complexes with stunning sea views.
name: Sentosa

excerpt: 82-hectare botanical garden with sculptures, a swan lake & significant collection of tropical trees.
detail_description: The Singapore Botanic Gardens, established in 1860 and listed as a UNESCO World Heritage site, spans 82 hectares of tropical paradise. It features lush lawns, ancient rainforests, tranquil lakes, and themed gardens. The National Orchid Garden within the premises showcases the world's largest collection of tropical orchids. For families, there's the Jacob Ballas Children's Garden with interactive features.
name: Singapore Botanic Gardens

excerpt: Huge observation wheel opened in 2008 for views of the city plus high tea & butler-serviced flights.
detail_description: The Singapore Flyer, the world's largest giant observation wheel, offers a unique experience for visitors to enjoy breathtaking views of the city. With its 28 glass cabins slowly revolving at 165m above ground level, it provides panoramic vistas of Marina Bay and its architectural landmarks. The observation wheel also offers various packages including high tea and butler-serviced flights, allowing guests to be pampered while taking in the stunning scenery.
name: Singapore Flyer

excerpt: Movie amusement park with sets & rides on themes from Hollywood to sci-fi, plus live entertainment.
detail_description: Universal Studios Singapore, located on Sentosa Island, is a sprawling movie-themed amusement park that offers an array of attractions and entertainment for visitors of all ages. With seven distinct zones inspired by popular films and television shows, the park boasts thrilling rides such as Battlestar Galactica and Jurassic Park Rapids Adventure. Guests can also explore intricately designed streets resembling Paris and Hollywood, shop for souvenirs, or enjoy a quick meal between adventures.
name: Universal Studios Singapore

excerpt: Rainforest zoo with tram rides, trails & viewing platforms to see wildlife habitats & exhibits.
detail_description: Singapore Zoo is a lush rainforest zoo offering tram rides, walking trails, and viewing platforms to observe wildlife habitats and exhibits. The zoo provides an immersive experience for visitors to witness various animal species in naturalistic environments. Additionally, it hosts events such as urban lifestyle festivals featuring culinary delights, arts, entertainment, and live performances. For those seeking a romantic escape from crowded spots on Valentine's Day, the zoo offers a serene setting for a laid-back private time with nature.
name: Singapore Zoo

excerpt: Night zoo with tram rides and walking trails through rainforest past elephants, tigers & leopards.
detail_description: Night Safari, located in the Upper Seletar Reservoir, is the world's first nocturnal wildlife park. It offers tram rides and walking trails through a rainforest where visitors can spot creatures of the night such as elephants, tigers, and leopards. The park houses about 2500 animals that are best observed after sunset. Guests can embark on guided walking tours or take a tram safari to get up close to these fascinating creatures in their natural habitat.
name: Night Safari

excerpt: This well-known, 2.2-km route features shopping malls & boutiques, plus restaurants & luxe hotels.
detail_description: Orchard Road in Singapore is a renowned 2.2-km stretch known for its abundance of shopping malls, boutiques, restaurants, and luxury hotels. Originally named after the fruit orchards and plantations that once occupied the area, it has evolved into a bustling shopping hub with over 5000 establishments. Visitors can explore a wide range of options from newer arcades like ION Orchard and Somerset 313 to established favorites such as Tangs and Ngee Ann City.
name: Orchard Rd

excerpt: The 70-ton merlion statue is one of the city's most iconic sights & is located in this park.
detail_description: Merlion Park is a must-visit destination in Singapore, known for its iconic 70-ton, 9-meter-tall merlion statue that spouts water into Marina Bay. This mythical creature with the head of a lion and the body of a fish has been an iconic landmark since it was built in 1972. The park is popular among both locals and tourists, offering picturesque photo opportunities and free entry.
name: Merlion Park

excerpt: Chinatown's maze of narrow roads includes Chinatown Food Street, with its restaurants serving traditional fare like Hainanese chicken rice, noodles and satay. Souvenir shops and indie boutiques dot the area, offering clothes, crafts and antiques, while Club Street is full of trendy wine bars. Cultural institutions here include the 1827 Sri Mariamman Temple and the ornate Buddha Tooth Relic Temple and Museum.
detail_description: Chinatown is a vibrant district in Singapore, known for its maze of narrow streets filled with traditional eateries, souvenir shops, and indie boutiques. Visitors can explore the area's rich cultural institutions such as the Sri Mariamman Temple and the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple and Museum. A visit to Maxwell Food Centre is a must for sampling local delicacies like Hainanese chicken rice and sugarcane juice.
name: Chinatown

excerpt: Little India is a vibrant cultural enclave with temples and mosques, street art and brightly painted shophouses. Along the main drag, Serangoon Road, unfussy canteens and hip eateries sit next to shops selling gold jewelry, colourful silks and fresh flower garlands. Nearby, Mustafa Centre welcomes shoppers 24/7. The ethnic district is liveliest during Hindu celebrations like the Deepavali festival of lights.
detail_description: Little India is a lively cultural district in Singapore, featuring temples, mosques, street art, and colorful shophouses. Serangoon Road is the main thoroughfare where visitors can find a mix of casual eateries, trendy restaurants, gold jewelry shops, vibrant silks stores, and fresh flower garlands. Mustafa Centre offers 24/7 shopping nearby. The area comes alive during Hindu celebrations like the Deepavali festival of lights.
name: Little India

excerpt: Verdant island with walking & cycling paths amid villages, old granite quarries & diverse bird life.
detail_description: Pulau Ubin is a lush island with scenic walking and cycling paths, surrounded by quaint villages, historic granite quarries, and a rich variety of bird species. It offers an offbeat destination for couples seeking a romantic getaway, with opportunities for proposals and intimate photography sessions. The island provides remarkable wildlife experiences and a chance to immerse in the old kampong atmosphere, as it is the last traditional village in Singapore where residents live without electricity using rustic methods.
name: Pulau Ubin

excerpt: Mall with restaurants & nightlife in a redeveloped, 19th-century commercial district by the river.
detail_description: Clarke Quay is a vibrant destination in Singapore, situated along the river and known for its lively nightlife, upscale restaurants, and entertainment options. This area has been redeveloped from a 19th-century commercial district into a modern hub of activity. As part of Singapore's historic districts, Clarke Quay offers visitors the chance to explore the city's rich heritage while enjoying contemporary amenities.
name: Clarke Quay

excerpt: Tang dynastyâ€“style temple housing religious relics, with ornate rooms & a tranquil rooftop garden.
detail_description: The Buddha Tooth Relic Temple, located in the heart of Chinatown, is a stunning Buddhist temple built in 2007. It houses what is believed to be a tooth of Buddha, displayed inside a solid-gold stupa on the fourth floor. The temple follows Tang Dynasty architecture and features ornate rooms and a tranquil rooftop garden with a large prayer wheel.
name: Buddha Tooth Relic Temple

excerpt: Classical & modern architecture converge in this large, vibrant museum of Singaporean artifacts.
detail_description: The National Museum of Singapore is a vibrant and expansive museum that showcases both classical and modern architecture. It is a popular destination for culture enthusiasts and those eager to expand their knowledge. The museum's permanent exhibitions, such as the Singapore History gallery and Living Galleries, present a captivating narrative of the nation's past. Additionally, the museum hosts various temporary exhibitions that delve into topics like supernatural beliefs in the region and Singapore's colonial history.
name: National Museum of Singapore

excerpt: A well-known historical landmark, this grassy hilltop park hosts events such as concerts & plays.
detail_description: Fort Canning Park, located in the heart of Singapore, is a historically significant site that has witnessed many milestones in the city-state's history. It has been home to 14th-century kings' palaces and played a role in the surrender of Singapore to the Japanese during World War II. Visitors can explore remnants of a 19th-century fortress, a Spice Garden inspired by Sir Stamford Raffles' experiments with spices, and the ASEAN Sculpture Garden.
name: Fort Canning Park

excerpt: Museum of Singapore & Southeast Asian arts housed in a restored municipal building dating to 1929.
detail_description: National Gallery Singapore is a museum located in a restored municipal building dating back to 1929. It houses over 8,000 contemporary works of art from Southeast Asia and aims to inspire creativity and inclusivity through art dialogues. The gallery emphasizes art from the 19th century to the present day and collaborates with renowned museums worldwide.
name: National Gallery Singapore

excerpt: Design, science & technology exhibits in a distinctive, modern, flower-shaped building.
detail_description: Nestled among the towering skyscrapers of Singapore, the ArtScience Museum is a striking modern architectural marvel designed by renowned architect Moshe Safdie. Its distinctive lotus flower-shaped structure serves as an emblematic cultural landmark where art, science, culture, and technology converge. Collaborating with prestigious institutions and organizations worldwide, the museum presents exhibitions that explore the intersection of technology and culture.
name: ArtScience Museum

excerpt: Lush, 10-floor retail complex with hundreds of shops & eateries, indoor gardens & a 40-m. waterfall.
detail_description: Jewel Changi Airport is a 10-floor retail complex featuring an array of shops, dining options, and indoor gardens. One of its main attractions is the lush indoor rainforest, complete with towering trees and a stunning 40-meter waterfall known as the Rain Vortex. The Shiseido Forest offers a sensory treat with its misty atmosphere and enveloping trees.
name: Jewel Changi Airport

excerpt: Unique park using giant statues & dioramas to retell historic Chinese legends & religious mythology.
detail_description: Haw Par Villa, formerly known as the Tiger Balm Gardens, is a hidden gem in the Pasir Panjang neighborhood that offers a unique exploration of Chinese folklore and mythology. The park boasts over 1,000 statues and 150 giant dioramas depicting characters from Chinese folklore and religion.
name: Haw Par Villa

excerpt: Scenic artificial lake with boating, perimeter trails & a public park with a bandstand.
detail_description: MacRitchie Reservoir is a popular nature reserve in Singapore, attracting joggers, nature enthusiasts, and water sports lovers. The 12-hectare park offers a variety of activities such as strolling along the waterside boardwalk, hiking on trails of different lengths, and renting canoes or kayaks. One of the highlights is the TreeTop Walk, a 250-meter suspension bridge above the treetops offering stunning views.
name: MacRitchie Reservoir

excerpt: Centred on busy Arab Street, Kampong Glam is known as Singaporeâ€™s Muslim Quarter. Its 19th-century shophouses have been turned into stores selling textiles and casual restaurants serving spicy Malay and global fare. Notable landmarks here include the golden domed Sultan Mosque and the Malay Heritage Centre, where exhibits focus on local history. Clothing boutiques, street art and trendy cafes line Haji Lane.
detail_description: Kampong Glam, also known as Singapore's Muslim Quarter, is a vibrant neighborhood centered around Arab Street. The area is filled with 19th-century shophouses that have been transformed into stores selling textiles and casual restaurants offering spicy Malay and global cuisine. Notable landmarks include the golden domed Sultan Mosque and the Malay Heritage Centre, which showcases local history. Haji Lane is lined with clothing boutiques, street art, and trendy cafes.
name: Kampong Glam

excerpt: Built in 1827, the city's oldest Hindu temple features a tower densely ornamented with deities.
detail_description: Located in Chinatown, Singapore, Sri Mariamman Temple is the city's oldest Hindu temple, dating back to 1827. The temple is dedicated to the Hindu goddess Mariamman, known for curing illness and disease. Its ornate tower adorned with deities is a prominent feature of the temple. Recognized as a national monument, it offers visitors a glimpse into Singapore's rich cultural heritage and religious traditions.
name: Sri Mariamman Temple

excerpt: Steel footbridge, opened in 2010, inspired by the curved form of the structure of DNA.
detail_description: The Helix Bridge, a stunning steel footbridge that opened its doors in 2010, is an architectural marvel inspired by the double-helix structure of DNA. Spanning 280 meters, this pedestrian walkway connects Marina Centre to Marina South and serves as a vital link to the iconic Marina Bay Sands resort.
name: The Helix Bridge

excerpt: Large aquarium & resort featuring 800 species of marine life in a variety of habitats.
detail_description: S.E.A. Aquarium is a large aquarium and resort that houses 800 species of marine life in various habitats. It's located within Sentosa and offers a unique setting for photography, especially for wedding photos. The aquarium's lighting and reflective glass may require some adjustments to capture the perfect shot, but they also offer a wedding photography and videography package for couples who want professional images taken at this stunning location.
name: Singapore Oceanarium

excerpt: White, sandy beach with a skate park, water sports & sports facilities, plus local food sellers.
detail_description: East Coast Park is a 15-kilometer stretch of sandy beach in Singapore, offering a variety of activities and amenities. It features a world-class Xtreme skateboarding park, water sports facilities, and sports amenities. The park also boasts smooth cycle paths and more than 300 kilometers of cycling and walking trails known as the Park Connector Network (PCN). Visitors can enjoy local food at the East Coast Lagoon Food Village or rent bicycles to explore the palm tree-fringed seaside.
name: East Coast Park
address: E Coast Park Service Rd, Singapore

excerpt: Sky rides offering views of the city & harbour, unlimited ride tickets & an in-car dining option.
detail_description: The Singapore Cable Car is a popular attraction that has been drawing tourists since its opening in 1974. It connects Mount Faber with Sentosa Island, offering breathtaking views of the city skyline, lush greenery, and sparkling waters along the almost 6-kilometer route. The ride provides an opportunity to admire the scenic beauty of Mount Faber, Sentosa Island, and Marina Bay from close to 100 meters above sea level.
name: Singapore Cable Car
address: 109 Mount Faber Rd, Mount Faber Peak, Singapore 099203

detail_description: Bird Paradise, located at the Mandai Wildlife Reserve, is a captivating destination for bird enthusiasts. With over 3,500 birds from various species, including flamingos and macaws, the park offers an immersive experience in eight walk-through aviaries representing different global biomes. Visitors can enjoy shows at the Sky Amphitheatre and get up close to birds in their natural habitats. Despite some static electricity issues reported by visitors, Bird Paradise promises an educational and enjoyable visit for all ages.
name: Bird Paradise

excerpt: Passenger & cargo hub with 4 modern terminals plus buses & trains to the city center.
detail_description: Singapore Changi International Airport is a bustling hub with four modern terminals and convenient transportation options to the city center. While there are plenty of accommodations in Singapore, staying near the airport may be necessary for early or late flights. History enthusiasts can explore WWII attractions such as museums and monuments detailing Singapore's Japanese occupation and prisoner-of-war camps nearby. Visitors can also enjoy outdoor activities at Changi Beach Park, East Coast Park, and Pasir Ris Park. The newly opened 3.
name: Singapore Changi Airport

excerpt: Peranakan culture is explored through interactive & multimedia exhibits in a historic 1912 building.
detail_description: The Peranakan Museum, housed in a historic 1912 building, offers an immersive exploration of Peranakan culture through interactive and multimedia exhibits. It is also home to an authentic Straits cuisine restaurant led by Executive Chef Raymond Khoo, serving three generations of traditional Peranakan recipes. The museum showcases the rich heritage of the Peranakans with thematic galleries covering various aspects of their culture, from wedding ceremonies to crafts and feasting.
name: Peranakan Museum

excerpt: Museum exploring the history & cultures of Asia & their shaping of contemporary Singapore.
detail_description: The Asian Civilisations Museum (ACM) in Singapore is a unique institution dedicated to exploring the rich history and diverse cultures of Asia. With its extensive collection of over 13,000 artifacts from various regions such as China, Southeast Asia, South Asia, and West Asia, the museum offers an immersive experience into the multi-ethnic society of Singapore.
name: Asian Civilisations Museum

excerpt: Leafy, tropical nature reserve surrounding a hilltop with walking trails & a visitor centre.
detail_description: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve, located just 12 kilometers from Singapore city, offers a lush and tropical escape for nature enthusiasts. Spanning 1.64 square kilometers, this reserve is a haven for hikers and bikers with its scenic trails. The park boasts diverse flora and fauna, making it an ideal destination for families seeking an off-the-beaten-path experience in Singapore. With free entry, visitors can immerse themselves in the raw beauty of nature while exploring this green oasis.
name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve

detail_description: Esplanade Theatres on the Bay is a renowned performing arts center located near Marina Bay, offering an array of international shows and performances. With over 37,000 shows hosted and 26 million guests over its 15-year history, it's a hub for cultural experiences. The expansive 60,000 square meter complex includes theaters, concert halls, and a library dedicated to arts and culture.
name: Esplanade

excerpt: Zoo & aquarium with a river theme offering boat rides, freshwater fish & animals, including pandas.
detail_description: River Safari Singapore is a unique zoo and aquarium with a river theme, offering visitors the chance to see over 5,000 animals in an environment designed to resemble their natural habitats. The park features two main zones: Rivers of the World and Wild Amazonia, where guests can encounter animals from various rivers and the rainforest. One of the highlights is the world's largest freshwater aquarium, as well as a panda exhibit featuring Kai Kai and Jia Jia.
name: River Wonders

excerpt: Scenic, paved walking path connecting to many parks with bridges, wildlife & city views.
detail_description: The Southern Ridges in Singapore is a picturesque 5.5-mile walking trail that connects several parks through a series of unique bridges, offering stunning views of the city and the Southern Islands. The trail includes the impressive Henderson Waves pedestrian bridge and Alexandra Arch, as well as the lush greenery of Hort Park. Along the way, hikers can enjoy picnic areas, botanical gardens, and even a war museum.
name: Southern Ridges

detail_description: Raffles Hotel, a historic landmark in Singapore, recently underwent a two-year renovation to revitalize its colonial charm. The hotel offers newly refurbished suites, including the elegant Palm Court suites with rattan-filled balconies overlooking the guest-only courtyard. Its storied halls have welcomed political dignitaries and pop stars alike since its opening in 1887.
name: Raffles Hotel

excerpt: Landmark Islamic house of worship in the Kampong Glam Malay Heritage District, with guided tours.
detail_description: Nestled in the vibrant Kampong Glam Malay Heritage District, the Sultan Mosque stands as a stunning landmark and a significant Islamic house of worship. This architectural gem, originally established in 1825 with contributions from Raffles and the East India Company, showcases an enchanting Saracenic design crowned by a striking golden dome. The mosque's current structure was completed in 1928 under the guidance of an Irish architect, blending Indian and Islamic influences seamlessly.
name: Sultan Mosque

excerpt: A former convent & school, this 19th-century structure now houses restaurants, bars & event space.
detail_description: CHIJMES, located on Victoria Street in the Downtown Core of Singapore, is a stunning historical landmark that was once a Catholic convent and school. The 19th-century structure has been transformed into a vibrant lifestyle complex featuring restaurants, bars, event spaces, and shops. Its neoclassical architecture, sprawling lawns, courtyards, and marble waterfalls make it an enchanting destination for visitors.
name: CHIJMES

excerpt: Lush vegetation of the tropical highlands & a tall waterfall in a soaring, contemporary greenhouse.
detail_description: Step into the Cloud Forest, a captivating world shrouded in mist and surrounded by diverse vegetation. Located within Singapore's Gardens By The Bay, this modern greenhouse showcases lush greenery and hidden floral treasures, along with a 35-meter indoor waterfall cascading from a mountain of verdant foliage. Visitors can also explore the adjacent Flower Dome, featuring plants from around the globe in a Mediterranean-like climate.
name: Cloud Forest

excerpt: Historically significant market street with a variety of shops plus Muslim & Western dining options.
detail_description: Arab Street in Singapore is a historically significant market area that offers a mix of traditional and modern shopping experiences. It is known for its vibrant night market, colorful textiles, aromatic teas, and indie boutiques. The area also features the iconic Masjid Sultan Mosque, which adds to its historical charm. Arab Street is a creative hub with restored shop-houses and street art, making it popular among both locals and tourists.
name: Arab St

excerpt: Waterway & entertainment district noted for modern skyscrapers & landmarks, plus dining & shopping.
detail_description: Marina Bay is a vibrant waterway and entertainment district in Singapore, known for its modern skyscrapers, iconic landmarks, and a plethora of dining and shopping options. The area boasts an impressive collection of art accessible to the public, including rotating exhibitions at Pan Pacific's Public Art Space and striking installations at Marina Bay Sands. The Ritz-Carlton Millenia offers a unique 30-minute iPod tour of its remarkable art collection.
name: Marina Bay

excerpt: Sprawling sanctuary housing over 400 bird species from parrots to penguins, plus play areas & cafes.
detail_description: Jurong Bird Park is a vast sanctuary that is home to over 400 bird species, making it the largest aviary in Asia. Visitors can witness over 5000 birds freely flying around them and enjoy various bird exhibits featuring flamingos, pelicans, macaws, and hornbills. The park also boasts an artificial waterfall where more than 600 birds reside. Guests can participate in feeding sessions and learn about the different bird species from caretakers.
name: Jurong Bird Park

excerpt: Aquatic amusement park with an aquarium, waterslides & a wave pool, plus tubing & snorkeling.
detail_description: Adventure Cove Waterpark is a top-notch aquatic amusement park located in Singapore, offering a wide range of attractions and modern facilities for visitors to enjoy. Whether you're seeking thrilling adventures or lighthearted fun, this waterpark has something for everyone. From exhilarating waterslides and tunnels to snorkeling with colorful fish and leisurely drifting along the lazy river, there are activities suitable for both adults and kids. Additionally, the park provides shopping and dining options to enhance the overall experience.
name: Adventure Cove Waterpark

excerpt: Reservoir & kayaking destination featuring a gallery with interactive exhibits on sustainability.
detail_description: Marina Barrage, located at Marina South, is a multifunctional destination in Singapore. It serves as a reservoir and also offers recreational activities such as kayaking and dragon boating. The modern architectural gem features interactive exhibits on sustainability and provides stunning panoramic views of the city skyline, including iconic landmarks like the Singapore Flyer, Marina Bay Sands, and Gardens by the Bay. This makes it an ideal spot for special occasions like wedding proposals or celebratory photographs against the backdrop of the cityscape.
name: Marina Barrage

excerpt: Green space along a waterway with walking & biking paths, benches, play equipment & a splash pad.
detail_description: Punggol Waterway Park is a picturesque green space located along a serene waterway, offering various activities for visitors of all ages. The park features walking and biking paths, benches for relaxation, play equipment, and a splash pad for kids to enjoy. With four distinct themes catering to different interests, the park includes the Nature Cove with its scenic views, the Heritage Zone showcasing lush greenery, and the Green Gallery preserving mature trees within natural terrain.
name: Punggol Waterway Park

excerpt: This snow centre features ice sculptures & winter activities, plus a 60-meter slope for sledding.
detail_description: Snow City Singapore is a unique indoor snow center that offers a refreshing escape from Singapore's tropical climate. Spanning nearly 3,000 square meters and maintained at a chilly -5 degrees Celsius, it provides an all-year-round winter experience. Visitors can enjoy various activities such as building snowmen, engaging in snowball fights, paintball in the Winter Shooting Arena, ice bumper car rides, and even trying out snow tubing on the 60-meter slope.
name: Snow City Singapore

detail_description: The Botanic Gardens in Singapore are a must-visit, offering a picturesque landscape with spiral walkways, lush greenery, and charming gazebos. This UNESCO World Heritage Site spans from Bukit Timah to Holland Road and features diverse flora. The newer section includes the Jacob Ballas Children's Garden, while the original garden boasts a variety of flowers and a board-walked rainforest area.
name: Botanic Gardens

detail_description: Nestled in the verdant Singapore Botanic Gardens, the National Orchid Garden showcases an impressive array of rare and exotic orchids. While it officially opened its doors in 1995, the garden's history dates back to the establishment of the Singapore Botanic Gardens in 1859. The orchid collection program, spearheaded by Henry Ridley and subsequent directors, led to the opening of an orchid house in 1899.
name: National Orchid Garden

detail_description: The Singapore Art Museum is a must-visit for families with older children, as it boasts an extensive collection of contemporary South East Asian art. Despite space limitations, the museum rotates less than 5% of its collection at a time, ensuring that each visit offers a fresh and diverse experience. With its stunning displays and ever-changing exhibits, the museum promises to be a beautiful and varied destination for art enthusiasts.
name: Singapore Art Museum

excerpt: This landmark Hindu temple displays elaborate architecture & colorful statues of deities.
detail_description: Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple is a stunning Hindu temple dedicated to the goddess and destroyer of evil. The elaborate architecture and colorful statues of deities make it a must-see landmark in Little India, Singapore. Visitors can explore the intricately detailed exterior and interior, but should remember to remove their shoes and dress respectfully. Surrounding the temple, there are specialty stores offering beautiful saris, spices, and accessories for those interested in shopping.
name: Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple
